<section class="hero">
  <div class="hero-stat">73%</div>
  <h1>of Estate Disputes Are Avoidable</h1>
  <p class="hero-source">Source: Legal Studies Research</p>
</section>

<main class="content">

  <p>Nearly three-quarters of all estate disputes could have been prevented with better planning, clearer communication, or professional guidance. These aren't inevitable tragedies — they're preventable mistakes.</p>

  <h2>What Makes Disputes "Avoidable"?</h2>

  <p>Researchers analysed hundreds of contested estates and found common patterns:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Outdated wills</strong> — Wills that didn't reflect current circumstances</li>
    <li><strong>DIY mistakes</strong> — Homemade wills with technical errors</li>
    <li><strong>Missing documents</strong> — Wills that couldn't be found or weren't properly stored</li>
    <li><strong>No communication</strong> — Family members blindsided by unexpected decisions</li>
    <li><strong>Ambiguous language</strong> — Unclear instructions that different people interpreted differently</li>
    <li><strong>Failure to consider claims</strong> — Not planning for likely family provision claims</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The 27% That Aren't Avoidable</h2>

  <p>Some disputes happen despite good planning:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Genuine disagreements about a person's wishes</li>
    <li>Complex family dynamics that no document can resolve</li>
    <li>Unexpected circumstances after death</li>
    <li>Bad actors who will contest regardless</li>
  </ul>

  <p>But even these situations are made worse by poor planning. A well-structured estate won't prevent all conflict, but it gives executors and courts clear guidance.</p>

  <div class="cta-box">
    <h3>The Tragedy</h3>
    <p>Most people who end up in estate disputes never expected it. They assumed their family would "work it out." They didn't realise that grief, money, and unclear instructions are a combustible combination.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>How to Be in the 73%</h2>

  <p>The steps to avoid preventable disputes are straightforward:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Get professional help</strong> — A properly drafted will costs hundreds; a dispute costs tens of thousands</li>
    <li><strong>Update regularly</strong> — Review your will after marriages, divorces, births, deaths, and major asset changes</li>
    <li><strong>Document your reasons</strong> — If you're making unequal or unexpected decisions, explain why</li>
    <li><strong>Talk to your family</strong> — Surprises create conflict; conversations create understanding</li>
    <li><strong>Choose the right executor</strong> — Someone capable, neutral, and trusted by all parties</li>
    <li><strong>Store it properly</strong> — Make sure your will can be found and is clearly the final version</li>
    <li><strong>Consider potential claims</strong> — If someone might challenge your will, plan for it</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The Real Message</h2>

  <p>Estate disputes aren't fate. They're usually the result of decisions not made, conversations not had, and documents not updated. The 73% statistic isn't about blame — it's about opportunity. With relatively simple steps, you can dramatically reduce the chance that your death leads to family conflict.</p>

  <p>Your family deserves better than a preventable dispute.</p>

